By Andrew Metzger and Daniel Gold

data.loc[data.Vegas_Favorite=='ERROR - abbrev_team','game_id'].unique() #Prints out the game ids of all of the error missing team for vegas favorite which will be manually changed in the nect section
array(['202012020pit', '202012070pit', '202012080rav'], dtype=object)

data.rename(columns={'position ':'position'},inplace=True)

data.Surface=data.Surface.apply(lambda x: 'fieldturf' if 'fieldturf' in x else 'grass' if 'grass' in x else x)
data.loc[data[data.Vegas_Favorite.isnull()].index,'Vegas_Favorite']='None' #Changed the null values in Vegas_Favorite to 'None' as neither team is the favorite to win
data.loc[data.game_id=='202012020pit','Vegas_Favorite'] = 'PIT' #Googled and put in the vegas favorite for the missing value for this game
data.loc[data.game_id=='202012070pit','Vegas_Favorite'] = 'PIT' #Googled and put in the vegas favorite for the missing value for this game
data.loc[data.game_id=='202012080rav','Vegas_Favorite'] = 'BAL' #Googled and put in the vegas favorite for the missing value for this game

1.3 Data preparation

By All

The following data preparation steps helped us to prepare our data for implementing various modeling / validation techniques:

  1. Since we need are analyzing house price, we derived some new variables (from existing variables) that intuitively seem to be associated with house price.

  2. We have created a standardized version of the dataset, as we are computing Euclidean distances to find houses similar to a given house

######---------------Creating new variables----------------#########

data['score']=data.apply(lambda x: x.home_score if x.team==x.home_team else x.vis_score,axis=1) #Score of the team of a player in a game
data['score_diff']=data.apply(lambda x: x.home_score-x.vis_score if x.team==x.home_team else x.vis_score-x.home_score,axis=1) #Score of the team of a player minus score of other team in a game
data['Vegas_Line']=data.apply(lambda x:x.Vegas_Line if x.Vegas_Favorite==x.team else -x.Vegas_Line,axis=1) #Changes teams that are not favored to win to a positive vegas line (as +3.5 means you are supposed to lose by 3.5 points)
data['favorite']=data.apply(lambda x: 'yes' if x.Vegas_Line < 0 else 'push' if x.Vegas_Line==0 else 'no',axis=1) #Categorical variable that determines if a team is favorited to win
data['win'] = data.apply(lambda x: 'win' if x.score_diff>0 else 'tie' if x.score_diff==0 else 'loss',axis=1) #Categorical variable that determines if a team won the game
data['covered'] = data.apply(lambda x:'yes' if x.Vegas_Line+x.score_diff>0 else 'push' if x.Vegas_Line + x.score_diff==0 else 'no',axis=1) #Categorical variable to determine if a team covered the spread (i.e. if vegas line -3, team wins by than 3 points or if vegas line +3, team loses by less than 3 or wins)
#creating a column to store the sum of passing and rushing yards
data['Rushing+Passing']=data.pass_yds+data.rush_yds
#creating a column to store the sum of rushing and receiving yards
data['Rushing+Receiving']=data.rush_yds+data.rec_yds
#creating a Boolean column that indicates whether the player is playing home or not 
data['player_is_home'] = data['home_team'] == data['team']
#the next column indicates whether the player is home or away: conveys equivalent information as previous column
data['home_or_away'] = data['player_is_home'].apply(lambda x: 'home' if x==True else 'away')
#creating a column that indicates the difference of scores between home and away team
data['h-a_score'] = data['home_score']-data['vis_score']                                                                
######-----Standardizing the dataset ----------------------#########

We observe that while home teams have a higher chance of willing by more than 10 points, home teams have a higher chance of losing by less than 10 points than are away teams. The following calculates specifically how more likely these values are

#the first line is how much more likely a home team is to win by a large margin than away teams are 
print((game_stats['h-a_score'] >= 10).sum()/(game_stats['h-a_score'] <= -10).sum())

#the next line is how much more likely a home team is to lose by a small margin (10 points) than away teams are

2.1.3 3) Does playing home vs.Â away affect different teams differently?

#aggregating all the game stats, keeping team and home_or_away separate 
team_ag_stats = ag_stats.reset_index(level = [0,1]).groupby(['team', 'home_or_away']).mean()

#pivoting the data for more structured data
team_score_stats = team_ag_stats.reset_index(level=1).pivot(columns = 'home_or_away', values = 'score_diff')

#column for extra net points (extra points a teams gains from playing over away, accounting for points conceded)
team_score_stats['extra_net_points'] = team_score_stats['home']-team_score_stats['away']
#Visualizing the extra net points by team to see if home or away affects teams differently

plt.figure(figsize = (24,7))
a = sns.barplot(data = team_score_stats, x = team_score_stats.index, y = 'extra_net_points'); 
a.set_ylabel('Average extra Net points from playing home', fontsize=22.5);
a.set_xlabel('Team', fontsize=23)
a.set_title('Average extra Net points from playing home, by Team', fontsize= 28)

2.1.3.1 What can we say are in common about teams that benefit more from playing home/away than others?
#aggregated data so that it doesn't lose the other statistics 
stats_by_team = ag_stats_sum.reset_index(level = [0,1]).groupby(['team']).mean()
stats_by_team['extra_net_points'] = team_score_stats['extra_net_points']

In the next code block, we will see the variables for a team that are most associated with a team having higher net points from playing home.

#the ten variables most negatively associated with 'extra_net_points'
    # If these variables are low for a team, it means that the team will likely perform significantly better at home
stats_by_team.corrwith(stats_by_team['extra_net_points']).sort_values().head(10).plot(kind='bar')
plt.ylabel('correlation with extra net points');
plt.title('Correlation between extra net points and the top 10 most negatively correlated variables');

Note that almost all of the above variables are associated with better offensive performance.

#the ten variables most positively associated with 'extra_net_points'
    #if these variables are high for a team, it means that the team will likely perform significantly better at home
stats_by_team.corrwith(stats_by_team['extra_net_points']).sort_values().tail(10).plot(kind='bar')
plt.ylabel('correlation with extra net points');
plt.title('Correlation between extra net points and the top 10 most positively correlated variables');

Note that a lot of the above variables are associated with worse offensive performance.

2.2 Analysis 2

By Will Krew

In the following code, I grouped the humidity, temperature, and wind speed of each NFL game into bins. Furthermore, I found the score of each individual NFL game.

game_humidity = data.Humidity.groupby(data.game_id).mean() # humidity for each game
binned_game_humidity = pd.cut(game_humidity,bins = 8,retbins=True) # binning humidity for each game

game_wind_speed = data.Wind_Speed.groupby(data.game_id).mean() # wind speed for each game
binned_game_wind_speed = pd.cut(game_wind_speed,bins = [-1,0,5,10,15,20,35],retbins=True) # binning wind speed for each game

game_temps = data.Temperature.groupby(data.game_id).mean() # temperature for each game
binned_game_temp = pd.cut(game_temps,bins = [5,17,29,41,53,65,75,85,95],retbins=True) # binning temperature for each game

game_scores = data.score.groupby(data.game_id).mean() # score of each game

In the following code, I split the data by the four main offensive positions (QB,WR,RB,TE), and then I found the total offensive fantasy points by position for each team during each game.

qb_data = data.loc[data['position']=='QB',:] #creating dataset for just QB data
qb_Off_SDP = qb_data.Off_SDP.groupby(qb_data.game_id).sum() # QB Offensive Fantasy Points for each unique game + team combination

wr_data = data.loc[data['position']=='WR',:] #creating dataset for just WR data
wr_Off_SDP = wr_data.Off_SDP.groupby(wr_data.game_id).sum() # WR Offensive Fantasy Points for each unique game + team combination

rb_data = data.loc[data['position'].isin(['RB','HB']),:] #creating dataset for just RB data (note, HBs are a special characterization of RBs, which is why they are grouped together)
rb_Off_SDP = rb_data.Off_SDP.groupby(rb_data.game_id).sum() # RB Offensive Fantasy Points for each unique game + team combination

te_data = data.loc[data['position']=='TE',:] #creating dataset for just TE data
te_Off_SDP = te_data.Off_SDP.groupby(te_data.game_id).sum() # TE Offensive Fantasy Points for each unique game + team combination

Creating a Dataframe to store the surface for each game

#creates a list of the unqiue game_ids, which represent each game in the dataset
allGames=data.game_id.value_counts().index
#converts the list into a series
allGames=pd.Series(allGames)
#makes a series containing the surface of the game with the corresponding index in allGames
surfaces=allGames.apply(lambda x: data.loc[data.game_id==x].Surface.mode())
#concatenates the surfaces and allGames series to create a dataframe
gamesSurface=pd.concat([surfaces,allGames], axis=1)

2.3.1 TOTAL YARDS

2.3.1.1 Barplot
#makes a series containing the total yards of the game with the corresponding index in allGames
totalYards=allGames.apply(lambda x: data.loc[data.game_id==x]['Rushing+Passing'].sum())
#creates a dataframe containing the surface and total yards for each game, and renames the columns to match what each column stores
allYardsDF=pd.concat([gamesSurface,totalYards], axis=1)
allYardsDF.columns = ['Surface', 'game_id', 'total_yards']
#use seaborn to create a barplot to show the comparison of means of total yards per game across surfaces
sns.barplot(y=allYardsDF.total_yards, x=allYardsDF.Surface)
#adding the title
plt.title('Total Yards Per Game Across All Positions By Field Surface')
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Total Yards Per Game Across All Positions By Field Surface')

2.3.1.1.1 Density Plot
#subset the data by each surface and then groupby the game ID to be able to sum the yards for each game
totalGrassYards=data.loc[data.Surface=='grass'].groupby('game_id')['Rushing+Passing'].sum()
totalFturfYards=data.loc[data.Surface=='fieldturf'].groupby('game_id')['Rushing+Passing'].sum()
totalASturfYards=data.loc[data.Surface=='astroturf'].groupby('game_id')['Rushing+Passing'].sum()
totalMturfYards=data.loc[data.Surface=='matrixturf'].groupby('game_id')['Rushing+Passing'].sum()
totalSturfYards=data.loc[data.Surface=='sportturf'].groupby('game_id')['Rushing+Passing'].sum()
totalAturfYards=data.loc[data.Surface=='a_turf'].groupby('game_id')['Rushing+Passing'].sum()
#each of these is an object that stores the total yards for each game_id
#use kdeplot to plot the density distribution of the yardage for each surface
sns.kdeplot(x=totalGrassYards)
sns.kdeplot(x=totalFturfYards)
sns.kdeplot(x=totalMturfYards)
sns.kdeplot(x=totalASturfYards)
sns.kdeplot(x=totalSturfYards)
sns.kdeplot(x=totalAturfYards)
plt.legend(title='Surface', loc='upper left', labels=['grass', 'fieldturf', 'matrixturf', 'astroturf', 'sportturf', 'a_turf'])
plt.title('Distribution of Total Yardage Per Game By Surface')
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Distribution of Total Yardage Per Game By Surface')

2.4.0.1 Demographics of Teams That Win
#As I only need score data for each combination of game_id and team, I can group by game_id and team and take the first entry
winner_data = data[data.win=='win'].groupby(['game_id','team']).first() #Subsetting and grouping the data to the teams that won
plt.pie(winner_data.favorite.value_counts()/winner_data.favorite.value_counts().sum(),labels=['Favorite','Underdog','Neither'],autopct='%1.1f%%'); #Creating a pie chart with the proportion of winning teams that were the favorite to win
plt.title('Demographics of Teams That Win'); #Creating a title for the pie chart

2.4.0.2 Demographics of Teams That Cover
#As I only need score data for each combination of game_id and team, I can group by game_id and team and take the first entry
covered_data = data[data.covered=='yes'].groupby(['game_id','team']).first() #Subsetting and grouping the data to the teams that covered
plt.pie(covered_data.favorite.value_counts()/covered_data.favorite.value_counts().sum(),labels=['Underdog','Favorite','Neither'],autopct='%1.1f%%'); #Creating a pie chart with the proportion of teams that covered that were the favorite to win
plt.title('Demographics of Teams That Cover'); #Creating a title for the pie chart

2.4.0.3 Underdog Vegas Line vs Score Differential
#As I only need score data for each combination of game_id and team, I can group by game_id and team and take the first entry
underdog_data=data[data.favorite=='no'].groupby(['game_id','team']).first() #Subsetting and grouping the data to the teams that are projected to lose (underdogs)
sns.lineplot(data=underdog_data,x='Vegas_Line',y='score_diff'); #making a lineplot of vegas line (x axis) vs score differential (y axis)
x = np.linspace(0, 23, 100); #Defining a linespace that starts at 0 and ends at 23 with 100 samples generated
plt.plot(x,-x); #Plotting the linespace with a slope of -1 that represents the relation between vegas line and score differential if vegas was perfect at predicting the score of games (all values above the line are when the underdog covered)
plt.title('Underdog Vegas Line vs Score Differential'); #Creating a title for the line plot

2.4.0.4 Underdog Teams Covering vs Vegas Line
binned_underdog_data = pd.cut(underdog_data.Vegas_Line,[.999,6,22],retbins=True) #Manually creating 2 bins for vegas line based on the trend identified in the lineplot above
underdog_data['Binned_Vegas_Line'] = binned_underdog_data[0] #Adding a Binned_Vegas_Line column to the underdog data that represents what bin they are in
sns.countplot(data=underdog_data,x='Binned_Vegas_Line',hue='covered'); #Creating a countplot of the number of underdog teams in each bin that cover
plt.xlabel('Vegas_Line'); #Creating a label for the x-axis
plt.ylabel('Count'); #Creating a label for the y-axis
plt.title('Underdog Teams Covering vs Vegas Line'); #Creating a title for the countplot

2.4.0.5 1 to 6 Point Underdogs That Cover
#As I only need score data for each combination of game_id and team, I can group by game_id and team and take the first entry
one_to_six_underdog_data = underdog_data[underdog_data.Binned_Vegas_Line==binned_underdog_data[0].value_counts().index[0]] #Subsetting and grouping the underdog data to the teams that were between 1 and 6 point underdogs
plt.pie(one_to_six_underdog_data.covered.value_counts()/one_to_six_underdog_data.covered.value_counts().sum(),labels=['Covered','Did Not Cover','Push'],autopct='%1.1f%%'); #Creating a pie chart with the proportion of teams that are 1 to 6 point underdogs that covered
plt.title('1 to 6 Point Underdogs That Covered'); #Creating a title for the pie chart
